{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Pierre Auguste Renoir - Country Dance - Google Art Project.jpg | title=Dance in the Country | artist=[[Pierre-Auguste Renoir]] | year=1883 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=180 | width_metric=90 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=Paris | museum= [[Musée d'Orsay]] }}
'''''Dance in the Country''''' (French: ''Danse à la campagne'') is an 1883 oil painting by French artist [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir]]. It is currently kept at the [[Musée d'Orsay]] in Paris.<ref name="Orsay">{{cite web |title=Pierre Auguste Renoir, ''Danse à la campagne'' |url=http://www.musee-orsay.fr/fr/collections/oeuvres-commentees/peinture.html |publisher=[[Musée d'Orsay]] |language=French |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref>
==Background== This painting was commissioned in 1882 by the merchant [[Paul Durand-Ruel]] who wanted works on the theme of the [[Ball (dance)|ball]]. He bought it in 1886, exhibited it for the first time in April 1883, and kept it until Renoir's death in 1919. A complementary painting on the same theme, named ''[[Dance in the City]]'', was also painted by Renoir the same year.<ref name="Orsay"/><ref name="Ullmann">{{cite book |title=Musée d'Orsay, art et architecture |first=Peter J |last=Gartner |publisher=Ullmann |place=China |year=2010 |pages=244, 245 |language=French |isbn=978-3-8331-5443-0}}</ref>
The painting, influenced by the artist's trip in [[Italy]] in 1881 where he found inspiration from [[Raphael]], marked an evolution of the painter who tried then to break away from [[Impressionism]].<ref name="Ullmann"/>
==Description== The painting depicts a couple dancing under a chestnut tree: the man is Paul Lhôte, a friend of the painter, and the woman is [[Aline Charigot]], who later became the wife of the painter. Both figures are painted life-size and occupy almost the entire painting. However, a table in the background on the right, and a hat on the ground, and a pair of faces below the level of the dance floor, can be seen. The woman who holds a fan in her right hand, displays a smiling face and looks towards the viewer. The scene is bathed in a bright and cheerful atmosphere, and the women's clothes use warm colors (yellow gloves, red hat).<ref>{{cite book |title=Renoir - Les classiques de l'art |publisher=Flammarion |year=2005 |place=Paris |page=130 |language=French |isbn=2-08-011445-X}}</ref>
